supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. Error in foliation: f. 1-103, f. 105-111 (from f. 26 there is also a second layer of foliation, which has been crossed out).

p.note: Top left corner: National Library book label with current signum.
Top of page, in brown ink by a modern hand: Breviar Beatissimae Sanctae Catharinae MCCCLXXIX.

binding.p: Medieval or early modern binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Hooked clasp. , stamped in gold: A 233.

decoNote.p: Blind tooled decoration consisting of sets of panels. Additional motives difficult to discern because of the worn leather.
The contains a small sculpted skull, probably made from bone.

binding.condition: Leather heavily worn. cracked and endbands exposed.

origin.p: Flanders , 16th century, first quarter. The origin is based on the saints mentioned in the calendar, several of which might indicate the Ghent-Bruges area as the place of origin. The manuscript seems to have been made for a man going on a pilgrimage to the Holy Land. There are two groups of prayers included for this special occasion (, ). There are also several portraits of what is believed to be the man who commissioned the manuscript and possibly his wife or a later owner (see Decoration).

acquisition.p: The manuscript might possibly be the psalterium donated by Anna Catharina Lindegren in , as mentioned by Gjörwell (1768) .

note.p: : St Vedast and St Amand (6 Feb.);
